No. 14, the second house from the left, in which Mark Twain lived when he returned from his world tour in 1901, has been sold by Francis S. Farr and the new owner will remodell same, according to the New York Times of April 19, 1938. It is said that during this residence, the author wrote "To the Person sitting in Darkness," The Tle of a
Eing and his Treasure' and "The Watermelons."

711039f-a.text:
10th Street, north side, west from and including Fifth Avenue, showing the Church of the Ascension on the N.W. corner. This was erected in 1850 by the Protestant Episcopal Church; this congregation moved here from its first location, in Prince Street (1839-50).
June 11, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.

711040f-a.text:
West 10th Street, southside, west from (No. 18, left) a point to the west of Fifth Avenue. The photographer is viewing towards Sixth Avenue to show a row of balconaded buildings bearing Nos. 20 to 38 inclusive and situated in the middle of this block. No. 26, reputed to have been the home of President Martin Van Buren, has recently been leased by Franklin P. Adams (F. P. A. of news fame) for alteration into modern one room
apartments.
une 15, 1938.
P. L. Sperr,
